Since it was one of my possible choices until recently, here is what I think:
- price - good, they offer nice discount even on the QV
- Carbon brakes? No need.
- Seats? You should try the "regular" Alfa seats, they are awesome, always have been.
- No heads-up for no reason.
- Too much carbon? Yes, lower trims look better in some ways (not the lack of red Start button).
- Quality? Not even half way there yet. Plastics and OEM feeling. Alfa always does this.
- Headlights? Don't like them, and the outline goes down until turnlights are on. No idea why.
- Taillights too suck.

Now, the worst:

- It doesn't looks as good as expected for the price. It costs as much as X4M or GLC C43 AMG Coupe, or an F-Pace and Velar. Needs few touches to become good though. (but hey, I hate Macans and Q8s) 
- Has to be red if you ask me and the paint has faults (looks different on plastic and metal)

- Profile also not nearly as good as expected. 
- No air suspension.
- the dna shifter and lack of configurable mode.

And I'd still love to have it because:
- Awesome sound.
- Glued to the road like no other SUV. Forget F-Pace.
- The steering, 12.1:1 ratio!
- Revvy, awesome sounding engine.
- It is so light in its class!
- The exhaust pipes.
- Those calipers!
- 505 hp engine that says the f-word to every other V6 petrol engine in the SUV world, every single one
Honestly, Alfa Romeo was one of those car makers that was just never really on my radar. Definitely a different story after this review!

This is a great SUV for those who can afford something equally as nice (and far more dependable) to drive around in while their Stelvio is in for repairs. And make no doubt about it; this vehicle will be spending a prodigious amount of time in the shop. A quick look at it's lineage, and stablemates should be more than convincing, and serve as sufficient warning. Aside from the fact that parent company Fiat isn't exactly known for it's reliability, their list of subsidiaries poses a specter that is even more frightening. (can you say Maserati?)  Add to this the fact that you are buying a car from a niche manufacturer (Alfa), which is owned by a company not known for it's build quality (Fiat), with a bastardized engine stuffed under the hood (Ferrari), and all I can do is wish you luck when you break down in the middle of nowhere, (and you will). 
That said, I'd still love to own one! (yes, I'm a hypocrite)

So I owned an old sad AlfaSud back in the day.  Rust bucket of unreliable everything.  Each day you'd wonder if it would start or arrive at the destination.  My spare cash was handed over to my mechanic so many times, I probably could have bought a way more expensive way better car.

When I saw one of these at an auto show I went to take a look.  First thing I touched was the gas tank cover, which felt as flimsy and plastic as my old Alfa.

I think (I may be wrong) that in the long term, the reliability and cheapness would definitely wipe out any of the initial excitement.  It may be fun for a test drive, but I just don't see this being a keeper in the long run.  Once bitten, twice shy.

Why dct‚Äôs fart:
  Volkswagen came up with the concept of retarding ignition timing at the crucial moment of the gear change, effectively mimicking the act of lifting off the throttle.  However fuelling and valve timing remain unaffected under this programming setup.  This results in excess fuel being deposited into the combustion chamber, remaining un-ignited.  When the next gear is engaged, ignition of the fuel is resumed via the spark plugs, and the excess fuel in the combustion chamber and exhaust manifold ignites creating that lovely ‚Äúvroomph‚Äù fart/burp that we all know and love.‚Äù  Info via https://www.torquingcars.com/tech-talk/tech-talk-why-do-dsgs-burp/

I actually quite like the front end design. BMW hasn't gone bonkers - the lights and grille look well proportioned. I guess it reminds me of slightly older BMW's - same with the interior - but to me that's a good thing!
It may be out of date, but the interior in the X3 is infinitely more beautiful and useful than the one in the newer BMWs. Same goes for the outside. They have lost the plot.

I've had my G01 LCI M40i for a little over a year now. I love it. No major complaints. The B58 is perfect for it. Handles fine. Suspension is decent, unlike the M's which are brutal. No complaints about the interior or exterior styling. I love the exterior styling. The interior is fine. My only complaint comes from the seats. My back doesn't like them. I have the heated and cooled seats. Wish the massaging seats from the M550 were offered. I got spoiled by those and I want them back. Otherwise, I'm pretty happy with the vehicle. I could do without the "mild hybrid" 48V BS and the resulting Auto start/stop, but otherwise, all good.

I've been driving this exact same car, same colour, same hybrid version since October 2021. So, here's my take on it. Brilliant!!! I even have the  real M-Sports seats (not these standard seats shown here), which are a delight, both optically and from a comfort aspect. The engine, in Sport Mode, with that extra battery power to boost acceleration, is really amazing. Top speed? Well, I live in Germany so am often on the Autobahn. 200kph is no problem and the car sits like it's stuck to the road. Handling is good, interior is pleasing and very functional, I agree that the front is not the most attractive car on the road. Negatives? The battery range is crap. However.... The displayed battery range depends on how you have driven the car before depleting the battery. If you were pedal to the metal all the time, the range after the next charge will be crap. If you were driving conservatively, accelerating slowly and using the cruise control, you will get a displayed range of over 40 km. What you won't ever get is the advertised 55 kms. My last car was the 2 litre X3 diesel. The car before that was the 3,5 litre 4 Series Grand Coup√©. I do have some small complaints, but on the whole am very happy. Oh yeh, I test drove the Mercedes GLC 300e Plug in Hybrid. Full battery, in October, 19 degrees C ambient temperature. Range, 19 kilometers. Yes, Mercedes bullshits too!!!

I came from a 981 Cayman S that I had driven daily for 10 years to an X3 M40i. I'm so impressed with the car, it's the perfect blend of practicality, comfort, and performance when you need it. Sure it doesn't quite have the poise and fun handling of the Cayman, but it's so much easier to live with in a 1 car garage. I was worried about reviewers saying the ride was harsh, to me on terrible Scottish road surfaces it's really comfortable without being wafty, really quiet on the interior too. Love that this model has proper buttons rather than touchscreen everything. Only thing I really miss is the Burmeister Stereo from the Porsche, the Harman Kardon isn't even close to that (although that was a ¬£3k option so can't expect it to be. I cross shopped with a Macan S / GTS, and the BMW was ¬£20-30k cheaper with similar options, a no brainer.
The facelift has only been available at the dealership for little over a year now. So definitely not a couple of years old.

Great car, does everything previous X5 40D family car did & more. Hybrid, any manufacturer/model - No-Way, modern financial rip-off. Negatives, lower seat driving position than an X5, if this is important. Strange wheel sizing especially when changing from summer to winter tyres (Had to buy 4 new tyres plus 4 new wheels at same time. No winter or all season tyres made by any Tyre manufacturer for UK market, for 21 inch BMW X3 LCI wheels - Yet available in N America). Due to date when ordered, wireless charging was deleted. No rear heated seats option when date ordered. Once car passes 3 year point from new, BMW's become expensive to maintain. Positives, drives like a sports car, not an SUV, reasonable petrol fuel economy, does everything X5 did previously. Highly recommend BMW LCI X3 M40I. NOTE: Tyre manufacturers need to keep-up with modern wheel sizing of new vehicles, so consumers can have options to drive safely on winter/summer/all season tyres in UK.

I have a theory about M; I think BMW is acutely aware of how "diluted" M cars have become in the balance between enthusiast driving and daily commuting. Starting with the current M3/4, it looks like they are making M even more hardcore and using the M-sport to satisfy all the people who want a more daily-livable M-car. Ergo the Mx40i cars getting all the badges, the mirrors, and even the special edition M-things like the retro emblem. Also why they are getting way more performant than they have ever been before.

I drove 3 x3/X4M‚Äôs to convince myself, coming from an F82. Ended up with an x4 M40i. I strongly advise potential buyers to try these Pseudo M‚Äôs without hate. Ultimately, the M40i drove very well, was better damped and sounded better. The x3/X4M just are not as intense as you‚Äôd hope, and when you consider gas/maint/insurance it‚Äôs not just a few hundred difference. Don‚Äôt forget the engine is tuned more NA on M‚Äôs which is frustrating in daily driving. I used to hate these M performance cars after 5 M‚Äôs but I put my ego aside and ended up enjoying these. Worth a shot.

I am glad to see your description mentions the true competitors this vehicle was designed to go up against.  It was not created to compete with the Stelvio Q because its based on the same platform and built in the same facility.  The way Stellantis has cast the line-up from smallest to largest is as follows  Tonale < Stelvio < Grecale < Levante.  Even though the Grecale is built on the same platform as the Stelvio, it is technically the larger of the two.  Its most direct competitor is the Porsche Macan that is where Maserati set their sights when they first started playing around with concepts years ago and was repeated again by its leadership.   What the Italians do with 4 Cylinder engines is truly impressive.  I have to admit that I am a Maserati loyalists, now having owned 5 in total.  There are a couple of things I see with the interior that need some polish so I imagine when I decide to go from my Levante to one of these I will be checking to see if that fit and finish has been fixed or if I am going to be requesting the dealership get the fixes done.  I have done that before on my Maserati's.  Yea sure it should be right from the start but it isn't and it doesn't stop me from buying it.

Sadly, Mercedes build quality have been shocking considering - and I'd opinion them as - they are the most premium German car manufacturer out of the top 3.  I find on their current range, the latch for the glove compartment levers are flimsy, so eventually breaks and the only way to then access the glove compartment is, to sit on the driver's side and without lifting the latch, to pull it towards you, and then lifting it.  Also, these electric tailgates are a huge faff which I could do without.  On their tall hatch back cars, I find that the bolts eventually give way and the hydraulic arms then no longer support the tailgate as it should.  So you end up driving the car with the entire weight of the tailgate resting on the bumper, which means, everytime you drive, you can hear squeeky noise coming from the back and much worse, you can end up with some cracked tail lights.

Lastly, the mood lightling?  Please!  These are features that again, one can do without.  The mood lighting looks aftermarket and so chincy.  If you've never driven a car with it, you may jump onto the hype of wanting to buy a car with one.  But once you have it, the novelty wears of extremely quickly and then, you'd start to regret your decision into why you've bought this feature in the first place, and how you wished you'd just save the money.  Put it this way, mood lighting is as useless as the panoramic sunroof: both of which, you as a driver can never or will ever enjoy.

And this is my honest opion about Mercedes, whether you like it or not.

Positioning / design of side mirrors to reduce noise / improve efficiency is clever, but it is also a completely standard and universal consideration on any decent car. It is like saying it is clever the car has a steering wheel. "Which does 0 - 62 in 5.6", might be a quirky way to assume people know it means mph and seconds but is sloppy and shows wider ignorance, in my opinion. Especially when 'litres' is repeated twice in the same sentence. Someone looking to put three child seats in the back will want to know if it can be done for sure (what a car review could be useful for and mention rival models that achieve this) not what someone 'reckons'. The car selects 'perfect position' for height but in the clip it seems to challenge her reach - a bit ambiguous. 'It turns out the car can do what it is meant to do, it can actually go off road' is introduced through commentary on the infotainment system instead of when reviewing its engine/handling/ performance making it seem contrived to me. Personally, I don't have confidence in this presentation.

I recently got a Macan loaner from the dealership and got to drive it for 2.5 weeks. There are a few design flaws I found.
1. Seatbelt warning would not go away even when i buckled it up. It wasn't every time but I noticed it at least 7-10 times for the 2.5 weeks. I would say that's a lot. Maybe it is only to this specific vehicle. 
2. The footwell right to the accelerator is too close to the pedal. when I shift my right foot from brake to gas pedal, the front of my shoe always gets snagged by the foot well. On the same note, when I try to hit brake from gas pedal, my shoe also gets caught by the wall and I almost lost the timing to brake a couple of times. Very poor design. It may not be an issue if you use both feet to gas and brake but most don't. (I wrote this b4 watching his video but just finished watching his and he said something about it too. It's just that I didn't understand him cuz he mumbles under his breath when he talks about it. I get annoyed when he does that. It's hard for me to understand some of his brit accents :(). 
3. The brake has almost no play. Way too sensitive. Either you brake hard or you don't. I wonder if Cayenne of 2020 is also like that. My 911 and 2017 Cayenne aren't like that. 
Otherwise, you can expect same excellent drivability and handling from Porsche. I wasn't a big fan of gear ratio either but I didn't haul anything at that time so it may be ok with loading.

Porsche Macan...one of the most overrated and overpriced cars on the market.  Base model over $60k with tax and what do you get?  The last generation Audi platform, out of date infotainment system (No android auto!), cramped rear seats and less trunk space than most SUVs in its class.  Mediocre performance and a bare bones interior.  Other cars/SUVS costing far less, provide far more safety and other features as standard.  But being Porsche, if you want them  expect to pay hugely inflated prices. To get to the same standard of equipment as say, a Mazda CX 5 Signature, you'll be paying close to $80k...basically double the price of the Mazda.  Correction, you can't get to the CX5  level  of features even at that price, since Porsche doesn't offer heads up display on the Macan even as an option!  
BTW the CX5 is significantly faster from 0 to 60 and when I drove the Macan and the CX5 back to back I preferred the Mazda's  combination of ride and handling.  Maybe the Porsche will be better at the limit but be honest, how often do we ever get there?  If you want "real" Porsche performance you need to at least buy the Macan S and then you will be pushing $100K with the options that are standard on "lesser" cars.
And once you own the Porsche you are going to pay inflated prices for servicing.  But surely you get better quality?  Well, no.  Consumer Reports ranks Porsche 13th in reliability well behind Lexus and Mazda and even beaten by Chrysler. 
So basically you buy a Macan in the hope it impresses your friends...but they probably think your are a pretentious idiot for wasting that much money.
